A fisheye lens might be a bit too much for a birdhouse.
You learn from your mistakes.
I should have known, since I already made one with a "normal" lens.
I'll tell you more this weekend once I've installed the second one I made.
Let's say the birds will have a better internet connection than mine in 2015.
Or at least, that was the goal.
The box that already contains a birdhouse benefits from the home's Wi-Fi.
There is still work to be done to connect the other one.
Well, I hung the other birdhouse during the day. Here's what it looks like properly placed in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?", don't I hear someone ask.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has a strange shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the nest box. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my setup around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire system is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box houses the battery.
Fully charged, it gives me about 4 hours of power.
I call this a feature. That way, the birds can also have some privacy.
Initially, I didn't know if the Internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and point it down towards the garden.
I could still do that when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
Now, for reasons that escape me for now, the camera is offline. It turned off barely an hour after sunset.
The battery charge might have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Perhaps it wasn't able to charge completely in a little less than half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one during a future revision.
A few more sensors would be good, I think.
And perhaps a battery capable of lasting the entire night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is way too much.
But I'm already looking at parts on Digikey, so I might just make a custom PCB for this use case.
Or not. We'll see.
And, it's still offline.
Super.
Given the solar panels installed on the house, the sun is really high only for about 90 minutes.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
In fact, on the USB-C board I was using to connect the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP didn't connect right away, let's wait a few minutes.
One hour later: still offline.
It seems like it's restarting in a loop and triggering Tasmota's reset feature.
I think the panel is just defective. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Look what I found in the workshop.
A 24 V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly hidden by a tree) that it drops to almost nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I will wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the best panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So, either something is wrong with this panel or my multimeter, or they changed the specs.
Good news, everyone!
They changed the specifications and the one I have is H.S.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12 V, 10 W panel.
That's why I don't delete my old emails.
Hey, look: the thing reconnected for about half a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of power. It would have only taken a little over two hours.
Guess what: the weather is cloudy today. So I'm not sure if this solar panel (probably broken) is able to generate enough energy to do anything.
Let's see.
Latest news: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
Maybe everything will turn off at sunset, but let's see.
By the way, I'm using the ping integration in Home Assistant to monitor if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not so bad.
